{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":36644,"duration_api_ms":36620,"num_turns":2,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"5a1dd2c0-9785-4efb-acee-d1a67fdf7d12","total_cost_usd":0.2108215,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22872,"cache_read_input_tokens":44213,"output_tokens":1830,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":22872,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":3,"outputTokens":1830,"cacheReadInputTokens":44213,"cacheCreationInputTokens":22872,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.2108215,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed 5 amendments independently. I agree with the planner positions on all 5. Two amendments (fr-8-f881e1e1, fr-8-19d961a9) are clear bugs where tmux adapter behavior diverges from process_backend in ways that violate design intent. Two amendments (fr-8-5aba0f56, fr-8-d2366c9b) are real but low-severity edge cases with straightforward fixes. One amendment (fr-8-63eaddd6) is a documentation-only suggestion where the system already behaves correctly.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-8-5aba0f56","decision":"accept","rationale":"The race is real and now exercisable via the new timeout path. After tokio::time::timeout fires, spawn_background_reap is called before the match arm exits scope, meaning the io_and_wait future (holding pipe read-end handles) hasn't been dropped yet when force_kill()+wait() execute. On Linux, SIGKILL terminates the child immediately so the child's write-ends close and wait() completes quickly, making the practical window extremely narrow. However, the fix (explicitly drop pipe handles before spawning the reap task) is trivial and eliminates the race entirely. A defensive one-line fix for a theoretically exercisable race in a timeout path is worth doing."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-d2366c9b","decision":"accept","rationale":"The arithmetic analysis is correct: attempt=0 causes saturating_sub(1) to produce u32::MAX, which cascades through saturating_pow and saturating_mul to hit the 60s cap. While the cap prevents unbounded delay, producing a maximum 60s backoff for a zeroth attempt is clearly wrong behavior. The type system doesn't prevent attempt=0, and a single-line early return guard (if attempt == 0 { return Duration::ZERO }) makes the function robust against misuse at negligible cost."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-63eaddd6","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that reqwest's timeout has different semantics than process-level SIGKILL, but the system already handles this correctly: the service safety-net timeout at request.timeout + 30s catches any case where the adapter timeout fires late or not at all. The 30s buffer being 'wasted' in streaming edge cases is not a defect — it's acceptable overhead. The amendment proposes only documentation changes for a nuance in timeout semantics that doesn't affect correctness. Marginal value."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-f881e1e1","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a concrete bug. The process_backend has classify_exit_failure() mapping exit code 127 to FailureClass::BinaryNotFound (terminal, no retry), but the tmux adapter unconditionally maps all non-zero exits to FailureClass::TransportFailure (retryable). This causes tmux mode to retry 'command not found' errors up to 5 times, wasting time on an unrecoverable failure. The retry policy explicitly treats BinaryNotFound as terminal, so the tmux adapter's hard-coded TransportFailure bypasses this design. The fix is straightforward: reuse or replicate classify_exit_failure() in the tmux error path."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-19d961a9","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a resource leak bug. The tmux adapter's invoke() runs prepared.cleanup() and prepared.finish() only after wait_for_session_exit() returns. When the service-level timeout fires and aborts the future via tokio::select!, those cleanup calls never execute. The cancel() method at tmux.rs:601-658 handles tmux session cleanup but never touches PreparedCommand, leaking temp files (schema/message JSON) and skipping failed-artifact preservation. The process_backend handles its timeout path correctly by cleaning up before exiting. The tmux adapter's cancel() must also handle PreparedCommand cleanup."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"953e1a93-d49f-4ad1-ac6e-7be9d2cf1324"}
